‐ We're closed.

44
00:04:31,271 --> 00:04:33,565
‐ Is, uh...is Scott around?

45
00:04:33,899 --> 00:04:36,485
I'm...here to hit the slopes.

46
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:39,821
MIA: Try the kitchen.

47
00:04:46,495 --> 00:04:50,123
‐ How can he not get caught?
‐ God only knows.

48
00:04:50,374 --> 00:04:53,836
‐ Maybe because his face.
He's dumb but cute.

49
00:04:53,836 --> 00:04:56,630
‐ [laughs] More dumb than cute.

50
00:04:56,630 --> 00:04:58,841
[Bebe laughs]

51
00:04:58,841 --> 00:05:00,843
Beef and broccoli and fried rice.

52
00:05:00,843 --> 00:05:04,012
And you take the egg rolls because
I took them all for Pearl last night.

53
00:05:04,930 --> 00:05:07,349
‐ Pearl? Is that your daughter's name?

54
00:05:10,394 --> 00:05:13,146
It's beautiful.
‐ Thank you.

55
00:05:15,816 --> 00:05:16,984
So is May Ling.

56
00:05:23,407 --> 00:05:27,661
‐ Sometimes...I still hear her cry.

57
00:05:37,337 --> 00:05:41,216
‐ Of course you do.
Because you're her mother.

58
00:05:42,050 --> 00:05:43,260
‐ She gone.

59
00:05:45,762 --> 00:05:47,306
I'm not her mother anymore.

60
00:05:47,306 --> 00:05:50,809
‐ Bebe, a mother is a mother,
and you will always be hers.

61
00:05:50,809 --> 00:05:53,020
‐ I leave her. I do that.

62
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:55,898
It doesn't matter what I want.
‐ No, it does.

63
00:05:55,898 --> 00:05:59,818
It matters. May Ling is out there.

64
00:06:00,319 --> 00:06:03,906
And if you want her, you have to find her.
Whatever it takes.

65
00:06:03,906 --> 00:06:06,241
‐ Find her?
You think it's so easy?

66
00:06:07,075 --> 00:06:09,328
You think I'm not
trying my best to find her?

67
00:06:09,328 --> 00:06:11,121
I'm illegal.

68
00:06:11,121 --> 00:06:14,541
If I go to police station,
they'll send me back.

69
00:06:19,505 --> 00:06:21,340
[bell rings]

70
00:06:24,927 --> 00:06:27,596
‐ Hey, hey. Uh, I didn't finish
<i>A Separate Peace.</i>

71
00:06:27,596 --> 00:06:29,348
What happens?

72
00:06:29,348 --> 00:06:32,142
‐ Um, Finny's in the tree,
and Gene shakes the branch.

73
00:06:34,102 --> 00:06:35,103
What do you think?

74
00:06:36,146 --> 00:06:37,397
‐ Decent penmanship.

75
00:06:38,482 --> 00:06:40,943
Is it still penmanship when
it's done with a paintbrush?

76
00:06:40,943 --> 00:06:42,528
‐ Uh‐‐
‐ Paintbrushmanship?

77
00:06:42,528 --> 00:06:44,446
‐ I meant about going.

78
00:06:44,947 --> 00:06:49,117
‐ I think I would rather finally
watch <i>Before Sunrise</i> like we planned.

79
00:06:49,117 --> 00:06:50,285
It's been weeks.

80
00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:54,456
So, uh, what happens next?

81
00:06:55,499 --> 00:06:57,960
‐ Um, Finny falls and breaks his leg.

82
00:06:58,502 --> 00:07:01,505
LEXIE: When that counselor discouraged me
from taking a harder math class,

83
00:07:01,505 --> 00:07:03,674
I found myself angry and confused.

84
00:07:03,674 --> 00:07:05,592
Our conversation took less than a minute,

85
00:07:05,968 --> 00:07:08,262
the same amount of time it took
for that metaphorical glass ceiling

86
00:07:08,262 --> 00:07:09,721
to form right above my head.

87
00:07:09,721 --> 00:07:12,558
‐ Mm.
‐ His sexism was telling me
loud and clear.

88
00:07:12,558 --> 00:07:14,810
That I would never go as far
as my male classmates.

89
00:07:15,352 --> 00:07:17,729
Sexist discrimination
is more than a hardship.

90
00:07:17,729 --> 00:07:19,857
It's the pervasive reality
of being a woman.

91
00:07:19,857 --> 00:07:21,608
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ And it's a reality I'm striving

92
00:07:21,608 --> 00:07:23,569
to change as we move
into the twenty‐first century.

93
00:07:23,569 --> 00:07:25,529
‐ Mm.
‐ As our first lady said,

94
00:07:25,529 --> 00:07:28,323
we as women can do more
than sit home and bake cookies.

95
00:07:28,323 --> 00:07:29,741
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ Glass ceilings are glass

96
00:07:29,741 --> 00:07:31,493
because they are made to be shattered.

97
00:07:34,913 --> 00:07:36,832
Well? What do you think?

98
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:41,336
‐ Um, yeah, it was‐it was good.

99
00:07:41,545 --> 00:07:44,047
I, I didn't know
that happened to you, so...

100
00:07:44,756 --> 00:07:47,176
Are, are we, are we still doing...

101
00:07:47,176 --> 00:07:49,261
‐ Okay, well, why would
I have written it if it didn't happen?

102
00:07:49,261 --> 00:07:50,304
‐ Guess not.

103
00:07:51,513 --> 00:07:55,893
I don't know, I guess I just figured
you would have...said something.

104
00:07:55,893 --> 00:07:58,145
‐ What, to get second guessed
for my experience?

105
00:07:58,145 --> 00:08:01,023
‐ Why are you getting so mad?
‐ Is this even about my essay?

106
00:08:02,608 --> 00:08:04,193
Is this about sex?

107
00:08:04,735 --> 00:08:06,486
‐ What are you...no.

108
00:08:08,363 --> 00:08:09,281
No.

109
00:08:10,741 --> 00:08:14,578
But prom and Homecoming
are basically the same thing, so...

110
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:19,917
‐ Okay, they are completely different.
When did Brenda and Dylan have sex?

111
00:08:19,917 --> 00:08:21,627
It was prom night, Brian.

112
00:08:22,294 --> 00:08:24,755
‐ Um, no, actually, it wasn't.
It was the spring dance.

113
00:08:24,755 --> 00:08:26,215
‐ The spring dance and prom
are the same thing.

114
00:08:26,215 --> 00:08:27,883
They just couldn't say that
because they were juniors twice.

115
00:08:27,883 --> 00:08:31,512
‐ Which is exactly why we shouldn't
use them as our sexual touchstone.

116
00:08:32,930 --> 00:08:35,307
That show is stupid, anyway.
It doesn't make any sense.

117
00:08:36,475 --> 00:08:37,392
Where's your faceplate?

118
00:08:39,686 --> 00:08:42,356
ELENA: I was very clear
when I ordered these cookies,

119
00:08:42,356 --> 00:08:44,733
27 days ago,
that I needed them Friday

120
00:08:44,733 --> 00:08:46,151
and tomorrow is Friday.

121
00:08:46,151 --> 00:08:48,320
Trip, get off the line.
I'm on the phone.

122
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:49,655
TRIP: Sorry, Mom.
BEV: <i>You could try</i>
<i>a different kind of cookie.</i>

123
00:08:49,655 --> 00:08:51,823
‐ No, a different kind of cookie
is not gonna work.

124
00:08:51,823 --> 00:08:54,159
You can't put a tiny message
in a different cookie.

125
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:55,911
Bev.
BEV: <i>Can you hang on a sec?</i>

126
00:08:55,911 --> 00:08:57,204
‐ Okay, yes, fine, I'll hold.
‐ I'm home.

127
00:08:57,204 --> 00:08:58,121
‐ Hi, honey.

128
00:08:59,623 --> 00:09:01,124
There's a problem with the cookies.

129
00:09:02,417 --> 00:09:05,295
‐ What cookies?
‐ The ones I've been talking about
for literally a month.

130
00:09:05,295 --> 00:09:08,215
The ones for Mirabelle's birthday party.
Dinner, everybody.

131
00:09:08,549 --> 00:09:10,509
‐ We got a fine at Windsor.
‐ What?

132
00:09:10,509 --> 00:09:13,303
‐ Mm‐hmm. She let the grass
grow over six inches.

133
00:09:14,012 --> 00:09:15,848
‐ Uh, is it all right
if Pearl stays for dinner?

134
00:09:15,848 --> 00:09:18,392
ELENA: Yes, of course, as long as
it's okay with her mother.

135
00:09:18,392 --> 00:09:20,435
Is it fine with your mom?
‐ I'm sure it's fine, yeah.

136
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:22,813
‐ Okay, great.
Can we talk about this later?

137
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:26,275
Uh, Moody, will you take the rolls
and put them on the table and also set?

138
00:09:26,275 --> 00:09:28,443
BEV: <i>Are you still there?</i>
‐ Yes, I'm still holding Bev.

139
00:09:28,735 --> 00:09:30,529
Mm‐hmm.
‐ Okay, yeah.

140
00:09:31,613 --> 00:09:34,241
Hi.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

141
00:09:35,409 --> 00:09:37,619
‐ She agreed to follow the ordinances
when she moved in.

142
00:09:39,204 --> 00:09:42,249
‐ Oh, great.
That's so great to hear that.

143
00:09:42,249 --> 00:09:45,043
You're a lifesaver.
All right, thank you, honey. Bye.

144
00:09:45,752 --> 00:09:47,754
Moody, don't forget the cloth napkins.

145
00:09:47,754 --> 00:09:49,548
‐ Hon.
‐ Yes, it's my fault.

146
00:09:49,548 --> 00:09:52,551
She asked for gas for the mower
and I just completely forgot.

147
00:09:53,010 --> 00:09:55,387
‐ Okay, but you're normally the one
who's out there with a ruler.

148
00:09:56,555 --> 00:09:59,641
‐ I know, but she works three jobs
and she made our dinner.

149
00:10:00,767 --> 00:10:01,727
How about you mow the lawn?

150
00:10:02,811 --> 00:10:05,022
Moody, don't forget
the forks are on the left.

151
00:10:05,022 --> 00:10:06,899
‐ I don't feel like
you're really hearing me here.

152
00:10:06,899 --> 00:10:09,109
‐ [door closes]
‐ Look who's here, finally.

153
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:10,986
ELENA: Oh, my goodness, Brian!

154
00:10:10,986 --> 00:10:14,198
How are you?
It has been so long.

155
00:10:14,907 --> 00:10:16,783
Why is it so hard
to get you to this house?

156
00:10:16,783 --> 00:10:19,036
‐ [chuckles] Thanks for having me,
Mrs. Richardson.

157
00:10:19,036 --> 00:10:21,622
‐ Always. Okay, Moody,
make sure everybody has a drink.

158
00:10:21,622 --> 00:10:25,000
We have strawberry, kiwi,
and diet peach Snapple.

159
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,753
And Lexie, get your brother and sister.
I don't know what's taking them so long.

160
00:10:27,753 --> 00:10:29,630
LEXIE: Yo, dinner.

161
00:10:31,548 --> 00:10:34,343
‐ Uh, hey. [chuckles]
‐ Hi, I'm Pearl.

162
00:10:34,676 --> 00:10:36,386
‐ Oh, you two don't know each other?
PEARL: No.

163
00:10:36,386 --> 00:10:39,139
‐ Oh, you're gonna love each other.
I'm sure you have so much in common.

164
00:10:41,433 --> 00:10:45,020
‐ No way. You must like
rap and basketball too, huh?

165
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:46,897
[Pearl chuckles]

166
00:10:48,899 --> 00:10:50,651
LEXIE: <i>It's called</i>
<i>the Million Woman March.</i>

167
00:10:50,651 --> 00:10:52,569
I just think that that
should be for all women.

168
00:10:52,569 --> 00:10:53,987
Like the Million Man March.

169
00:10:53,987 --> 00:10:56,156
‐ Yeah, but that was actually
just black men.

170
00:10:56,156 --> 00:10:57,783
TRIP: Yo, can I get a roll?

171
00:10:58,575 --> 00:11:00,619
Dude, don't be a little bitch, bro.
‐ Hey, Trip.

172
00:11:00,619 --> 00:11:01,787
TRIP: Give me the rolls.
‐ He just said bitch.

173
00:11:01,787 --> 00:11:05,207
‐ Moody, I don't like that language.
LEXIE: I just think that there should be
a march for everyone.

174
00:11:05,207 --> 00:11:06,917
Otherwise, it's outdated and sexist.

175
00:11:06,917 --> 00:11:09,461
‐ Mm, sexist.
Your favorite word.

176
00:11:10,045 --> 00:11:11,880
‐ Like the March on Washington.
Right, Mom?

177
00:11:11,880 --> 00:11:14,174
You said that was for everyone.
‐ It was amazing.

178
00:11:14,424 --> 00:11:17,511
Young, old, white, African‐American.

179
00:11:17,928 --> 00:11:20,806
Religious leaders,
activists, union members.

180
00:11:20,806 --> 00:11:24,476
Just a beautiful blend of people.
Including Dr. King, of course.

181
00:11:25,060 --> 00:11:27,479
I remember being a child
and even at that moment,

182
00:11:27,479 --> 00:11:29,147
I knew it was monumental.

183
00:11:29,940 --> 00:11:32,192
It really was a dream. It was.

184
00:11:32,860 --> 00:11:35,028
LEXIE: It's like the
Minority Achievement Committee.

185
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:37,489
Right, like, I of course
support minorities achieving,

186
00:11:37,489 --> 00:11:39,449
and yet, I can't go
to any of those meetings.

187
00:11:39,908 --> 00:11:42,077
‐ Well, the group
is kind of about, you know,

188
00:11:42,077 --> 00:11:44,705
black students
supporting each other, so...

189
00:11:44,705 --> 00:11:48,208
‐ You think?
‐ You know, no one's talking to you, Izzy.

190
00:11:48,208 --> 00:11:49,918
‐ Yeah, no one wants
to hear you talk, Lexie.

191
00:11:49,918 --> 00:11:52,421
‐ Okay, you two, please don't start.
ELENA: Brian, I noticed

192
00:11:52,421 --> 00:11:54,381
a real need for that at the school

193
00:11:54,381 --> 00:11:56,758
when I was dealing with Pearl
and her counselor.

194
00:11:58,051 --> 00:12:00,012
‐ Wait, what, what happened
with the counselor?

195
00:12:00,012 --> 00:12:01,597
‐ He was a jerk.
‐ Yeah.

196
00:12:01,597 --> 00:12:04,016
Mr. Bowers wouldn't let Pearl
switch to Algebra 2.

197
00:12:04,892 --> 00:12:07,227
PEARL: But Elaine helped.
She fixed it,

198
00:12:07,227 --> 00:12:08,645
so I'm really grateful for that.

199
00:12:09,438 --> 00:12:12,149
‐ What about Lilith Fair?
Is that sexist?

200
00:12:12,149 --> 00:12:14,484
‐ What is Lilith Fair?
‐ It's your worst nightmare.

201
00:12:14,484 --> 00:12:15,944
BILL: Trip.
‐ No wonder they call you "Ellen."

202
00:12:15,944 --> 00:12:18,363
BILL: Trip Richardson!
I said enough!

203
00:12:26,163 --> 00:12:28,582
‐ I'm sorry, why do they
call your sister "Ellen"?

204
00:12:29,333 --> 00:12:30,876
‐ Like DeGeneres, Mom.

205
00:12:32,127 --> 00:12:33,462
‐ Because she's funny?

206
00:12:35,214 --> 00:12:36,089
‐ No.

207
00:12:43,889 --> 00:12:47,267
MIA: Um, it was last winter.
Um, she was a young mother.

208
00:12:47,976 --> 00:12:52,231
The baby was‐‐ is Chinese.
Just a couple months old.

209
00:12:52,648 --> 00:12:55,317
She has a tiny red dot on her scalp.

210
00:12:55,609 --> 00:12:57,861
‐ It wasn't this station,
but yeah, I heard about it.

211
00:12:57,861 --> 00:13:00,948
‐ So if I wanted to know
where the baby ended up...

212
00:13:00,948 --> 00:13:02,491
‐ I'd try the police.

213
00:13:05,494 --> 00:13:09,998
‐ Right. If, um, is there anybody else
I, I could also talk to?

214
00:13:09,998 --> 00:13:12,376
Just to be vigilant.
‐ Only the police.

215
00:13:13,001 --> 00:13:15,087
They're your best bet
if you want to find that baby.

216
00:13:15,838 --> 00:13:17,214
‐ Okay, thanks.
‐ Good luck.

217
00:13:17,214 --> 00:13:18,048
‐ Uh‐huh.

218
00:13:31,270 --> 00:13:33,522
‐ You didn't have to drive me.
‐ Oh, no, it was easy.

219
00:13:33,522 --> 00:13:35,899
I was running errands
on this side of town anyway.

220
00:13:35,899 --> 00:13:39,611
But I don't know how I'm gonna
get it all done before Saturday.

221
00:13:39,611 --> 00:13:43,240
‐ Right. It's essential a one‐year‐old
have a night to not remember.

222
00:13:44,783 --> 00:13:49,288
‐ You could help me if you're available.
I, I could use the extra set of hands.

223
00:13:49,288 --> 00:13:51,623
Although, maybe you're
going to Homecoming or‐‐

224
00:13:51,623 --> 00:13:52,583
‐ I'm not, Mom.

225
00:13:55,252 --> 00:13:57,212
‐ You know, you don't
have to go with a date.

226
00:13:57,212 --> 00:13:58,839
You could go with a group of girlfriends.

227
00:14:00,841 --> 00:14:02,384
What about April?
‐ Mom.

228
00:14:03,552 --> 00:14:04,761
‐ What, I...

229
00:14:08,348 --> 00:14:10,309
Is she the one
calling you names at school?

230
00:14:17,149 --> 00:14:18,442
[scoffs]

231
00:14:18,442 --> 00:14:21,904
I remember when I was in 7th grade
and Linda got boobs.

232
00:14:22,279 --> 00:14:24,031
And I was concave.

233
00:14:24,948 --> 00:14:28,368
And all the boys were flirting with her
and snapping her bra,

234
00:14:29,036 --> 00:14:31,163
and I didn't have boobs, so...

235
